While other Mormon leaders and supposed prophets have also commented about the inferiority of blacks and other races in their eyes.   “Let the BLACKS of the south be free, and our community is overrun with paupers, and a reckless mass of human beings, uncultivated, untaught and unaccustomed to provide for themselves the necessaries of life— endangering the chastity of every female who might by chance be found in our streets—our prisons filled with convicts, and the HANG-MAN WEARIED with executing the functions of his office!....... Insensible to feeling must be the heart, and low indeed must be the mind, that would consent for a moment, to see his fair daughter, his sister, or perhaps, his bosom companion, in the embrace of a NEGRO!...(Joseph Smith, as printed in the Messenger and Advocate, Vol. 2, pp. 299-301).<br>
<br>
Mormon apostle Mark E. Petersen said in 1954 at BYU “Let us consider the great mercy of God for a moment. A Chinese, born in China with A DARK SKIN, and with all the handicaps of that race seems to have little opportunity. But think of the mercy of God to Chinese people who are willing to accept the gospel in spite of whatever they might have done in the pre-existence to justify being born over there as chinamen, if they now, in this life, accept the gospel and live it the rest of their lives they can have the Priesthood, go to the temple and receive endowments and sealings, and that means they can have exaltation. Isn't the mercy of God marvelous?<br>
<br>
Brigham Young: Death to inter-racial couples:<br>
“Shall I tell you the law of God in regard to the African Race? If the white man who belongs to the chosen seed mixes his blood with the seed of Cain, the penalty, under the law of God, is death on the spot. This will always be so.” (Journal of Discourses, Vol. 10, page 110)<br>
<br>
John Taylor, the third President of the Mormon Church, spoke about abolitionist Horace Greeley after Greeley visited Utah:<br>
<br>
“... I would not talk to him: I felt myself SUPERIOR to such a mean contemptible cur. I knew he was not after truth, but falsehood. This Greeley is one of their popular characters in the East, and one that supports the stealing of NIGGERS and the underground railroad....he is one of the prominent newspaper editors in the Eastern country, and he is a POOR, MISERABLE CURSE.” (Journal of Discourses, Vol. 5, page 119)<br>
<br>
